paragraphs.text:
%spark

val df = spark.read.parquet("/odsc/books_clean.parquet")
df.createOrReplaceTempView("books")
df.printSchema

paragraphs.text:
%md
### Observations
1. Books without a large number of ratings are easily skewed
2. Let's figure out how many average number of ratings exist for each average_rating

msg.data:
Observations

  1. Books without a large number of ratings are easily skewed
  2. Let’s figure out how many average number of ratings exist for each average_rating

paragraphs.text:
%sql
select
  count(*) as total,
  avg(ratings_count) as avg_rating_count,
  average_rating from books
  where average_rating >= 5.0
  group by average_rating

paragraphs.title: Manually Bucketize the discrete ranges of average_ratings
paragraphs.text:
%spark

val conditional_bucketing = df.withColumn("rating_group",
  when(col("average_rating") < 1.0, 0).
  when(col("average_rating") < 2.0, 1).
  when(col("average_rating") < 3.0, 2).
  when(col("average_rating") < 4.0, 3).
  when(col("average_rating") < 5.0, 4).
  otherwise(5)
)

conditional_bucketing.createOrReplaceTempView("books_bucketed_conditionally")

paragraphs.text:
%md
### What have we learned?
1. That Reviews done on Good Reads can be trusted if the number of reviews on a book is greater than a minimal threshold
2. In the case of books scored between (3.0-4.0] and [4.0 - 5.0) (falling into buckets 3 and 4). We can use the p10 of 18 to initially filter groups 3/4
3. We will need to look to see how many text based reviews are left on these books to. The logic being people who loved or hated a book enough leave a review.

paragraphs.text:
%md
### Where we have arrived.
1. This data is missing some crutial information if we want to capture honest reviews (like category, publisher, publish date)
2. In order to do more with this dataset we have to go back to get more data
3. Luckily GoodReads has a developer API (and even luckier I've already imported more detailed information)
4. Next we are going to learn how to do ETL (extract, transform, load) Jobs. This helps us build better data to make Recommendations with

Up Next: [4-Spark-ETL](http://localhost:8080/#/notebook/2ERYSKY63)
